<ITEM>XXXIX. A challenge that might have been
&s;pared. <HI>Philalethes</HI> genteely call'd a match|le&s;s
Lyar.</ITEM>
<ITEM>XL. <HI>Marquis de l'Ho&s;pital</HI> u&s;es as much cere|mony
as <HI>Euclid.</HI> Acquitted of a double error.</ITEM>
<ITEM>XLI. <HI>Philalethes</HI> acquitted of a charge brought
again&s;t him. Writes for the information of
&s;ome Great Churchmen. Fal&s;ely accu&s;ed.</ITEM>
<ITEM>XLII. Declamation unan&s;wered.</ITEM>
<ITEM><PB REF="7">
XLIII. Di&s;cretion of <HI>Philalethes.</HI> What uni|formity
among Analy&s;ts.</ITEM>
<ITEM>XLIV. A country &s;warming with mathemati|cians.
<HI>Philalethes</HI>'s apprehen&s;ion for Reli|gion
in that country.</ITEM>
<ITEM>XLV, XLVI, XLVII, XLVIII. Mode&s;ty
and &s;igns of grace in the <HI>Author of the Ana|ly&s;t.</HI>
